<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>RuneQuest</title>
    <style>
        html, body {
            height: 100%;
            margin: 0;
        }

        body {
            background-color: #0d183a;
            color: white;
        }

        .top-bar {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            align-items: center;
            padding-left: 20px;
            padding-right: 20px;
            background-color: #1c2b5a;
            border-bottom: 2px solid white;
        }

        .container {
            display: flex;
            flex: 1;
            height: calc(100% - 82px);
        }

        .box-1, .box-2 {
            flex: 1;
            padding-left: 20px;
            padding-right: 20px;
        }

        .box-1 {
            border-right: 2px solid white;
        }

    </style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="top-bar">
    <h1>RuneQuest</h1>
</div>

<div class="container">
    <div class="box-1">
        <h2>About the game</h2>
        <strong>Title:</strong> RuneQuest<br>
        <strong>Developer:</strong> Onno te Voortwis<br>
        <strong>Genre:</strong> 2D Text-Based Grid RPG<br>
        <strong>Gameplay:</strong> Crafting, Collecting, PvE
        <p>RuneQuest, developed by Onno te Voortwis, is a captivating 2D text-based RPG set in a dynamically generated
            grid world. Players are immersed in a realm where strategic exploration, extensive crafting, resource
            collection, and thrilling PvE battles intertwine to create a richly detailed and engaging adventure.

        <h2>Gameplay Mechanics</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <h3>Grid-Based Exploration:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Grid Movement:</strong> The game world is divided into a grid, with each cell
                        representing different terrain types, resources, or challenges. Players navigate the grid using
                        text commands (e.g., "move north", "move east"), or use the buttons to move.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Dynamic Environments:</strong> Each cell can host forests, mountains, lakes, dungeons,
                        or villages, offering a diverse landscape to explore.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <h3>Resource Collection:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Gathering:</strong> Players collect resources by moving into specific cells. Forests may
                        yield wood, mountains provide ores, and lakes offer fish and water.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <h3>Crafting System:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Recipes and Blueprints:</strong> Players can craft tools, weapons, armor, and various
                        items using collected resources.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <h3>Player vs Environment (PvE):</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Combat Encounters:</strong> Engage in turn-based battles against various enemies, from
                        wild beasts to mythical creatures. Strategic use of weapons, skills, and items is crucial for
                        victory.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>

        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="box-2">
        <h2>Start a New Game</h2>
        <form action="/index" method="GET">
            <input type="hidden" name="command" value="load fresh">
            <button type="submit">New Game</button>
        </form>

        <br/>
        <h2>Save files:</h2>
        <ul>
            {% for item in items %}
                <li>
                    <form action="/index" method="GET">
                        <input type="hidden" name="command" value="load {{ item }}">
                        <button type="submit">{{ item[:-5] }}</button>
                    </form>
                </li>
            {% endfor %}
        </ul>
    </div>
</div>
</body>
</html>